{
  "doc_id": "8501",
  "text": "The formyl group donor in the formylation reaction is 10-formyl-THF [CITATION_1] . S. cerevisiae contains two C 1 -THF synthase enzymes for the synthesis of 10-formyl-THF, one in the mitochondria and the other in the cytoplasm, encoded by MIS1 and ADE3, respectively (see reference 1 for a review). Both the cytoplasmic and mitochondrial enzymes are trifunctional polypeptides with three enzyme activities: 10-formyl-THF synthetase, 5,10-methenyl-THF cyclohydrolase, and NADP-dependent 5,10-methylene-THF dehydrogenase. S. cerevisiae also expresses a monofunctional NAD-dependent 5,10-methylene-THF dehydrogenase in the cytoplasm, encoded by the MTD1 gene [CITATION_2] . The ADE3 and MTD1 gene products are responsible for cytoplasmic one-carbon interconversions, whereas the MIS1 gene product is responsible for mitochondrial one-carbon interconversions [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
